result.execSummary:
The defendant Justin T. Zimmerman was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Cases 14CM353 and 15CM88 called together at 3:30 pm [Clerk SH]
Defendant Justin T. Zimmerman in court with Attorney Whitney Hagemann. ADA Monica J. Hall appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
ADA Hall submits stipulation and order to dismiss case 14CM353

Constitutional rights given; plea of "No Contest" entered; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; Court finds the plea has been entered freely, voluntarily, intelligently and accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders JOC entered.
On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Count #2

On Count #1, the Court sentences the Defendant to:
--serve 30 days in Jefferson County Jail, with Huber/Work-release privileges; to commence 1/15/16 by 6:00 pm 
--Defendant is required to report for commencement and service of jail sentence with absolute sobriety and without controlled substances in system; non-compliance will result in loss of Huber privileges without further process.
--Days credit for time already served: 1 day
--to pay costs of $243 + $200 DNA Surcharge = $443; APPLY CASH BOND AND RETURN REMAINDER
Recess: 3:44 pm

Defendant Justin T. Zimmerman in court with Attorney Whitney Hagemann. ADA  Jeffrey Martin Shock appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Atty Hagemann informs the Court that they are ready to proceed to trial on each case
ADA Shock confirms the State is ready to proceed

Court orders that a different panel needs to be brought in for each day
1 alternate; 4 strikes each
jurors may take notes and ask questions
No Miranda Goodchild issues in either case
Court informs parties that if a felony matter proceeds, likely these cases will be bumped. If parties do not hear from Court's JA - they should plan on proceeding to trial as currently scheduled.
Court reminds Mr. Zimmerman that today is the last date to enter pleas on matter
ADA Shock informs the Court that on case 14CM353 the State will have 3 witnesses
Atty Hagemann indicates that they will have no additional witnesses
ADA Shock informs the Court that on case 15CM88 the State will have 4 witnesses
Atty Hagemann indicates that they will have no additional witnesses
Counsel agree 1 day is needed for each trial
ADA Shock requests leave to file motion to impeach the Defendant by the end of day; No objection from Defense - Court grants
Court informs parties that they will address motion at the beginning of trial
ADA Shock informs the Court that upon review of file, unsure if citizen has actually been served
Court orders State to provide update to Defense and Court by end of day
Recess: 9:33 am
